Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
setMsvMode(25.10)                                            setMsvMode(25.10)

Name
       setMsvMode - Sets the special handling for inter-domain nets and to use
       effective power domains for ISO/LS insertion

Syntax
       setMsvMode

       [-help]

       [-allowNestedDefaultDomain {true | false}]

       [-allowPowerDomainMinGapZero {true | false}]

       [-checkAllNetsForDomainCrossing {true | false}]

       [-handleBackToBackIsolation {true | false}]

       [-handlePD {true|false}]

       [-handlePDComplex {true|false}]

       [-honorCpfGlobalConnectionSpecForAoBuffer {true | false}]

       [-honorCpfGlobalConnectionSpecForShifter {true | false}]

       [-honorDotLibRelatedPGPin {true | false}]

       [-honorEffectiveDomainForIsoLsInsertion {true | false}]

       [-markIsoEnablePinAsAlwaysOn {true | false}]

       [-notUseTopFTermDomainForVoltage {true|false}]

       [-reset]

       [-shareWellAOBufferingSupport {true|false}]

       [-upf_allow_shifter_voltage_mismatch {true|false}]

       [-upf_insert_on_floating_pins {true|false}]

       Sets  the  special  handling for inter-domain nets and to use effective
       power domains for ISO/LS insertion.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs a brief description that includes the type  and  default
              information for each setMvsMode parameter.

              For  a  detailed  description of the command and all its parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man setMvsMode

       -allowNestedDefaultDomain {true | false}
              Allows a non-default power domain member to be logically  nested
              in  a default power domain. This default power domain member has
              fence constraint.

              By default, due to grouping, the fence constraint  is  lost  for
              the non-default power domain member. Set true to enable.

              In  the  netlist:  modules HInst11 and HInst12 are under HInst1;
              and HInst1 is under the top.

              You have the following:

              create_power_domain -instances HInst1

              create_power_domain -default -instances {HInst11 HInst12}...

              That means HInst11 and HInst12 are cut from  HInst1  to  default
              power  domain. If there is a fence/region constraint for HInst11
              and HInst12 in default  power  domain,  then  please  turn  this
              global  on.  Otherwise, the fence/region for HInst11 and HInst12
              will be lost.

              Default: true

       -allowPowerDomainMinGapZero {true | false}
              Allows users to set power domain zero minGap.

              Default: true

       -checkAllNetsForDomainCrossing {true | false}
              Checks all the nets for domain crossings. Set true to enable.

              Default: true

       -handleBackToBackIsolation {true | false}
              Supports back-to-back isolation insertion along one cross-domain
              net based on the CPF ISO rule. Set true to enable.

              Default: false

       -handlePD {true|false}
              Routes intra-power domain and global nets using  the  specifica-
              tions  of  the power domains. On using this option, earlyGlobal-
              Route routes intra-power domain nets only within their power do-
              mains. Global nets that do not connect with a  power  domain  do
              not get routed through that power domain.

              Default: true

       -handlePDComplex {true|false}
              Routes  nets belonging to more than one power domain so that the
              routing does not violate power domain boundaries, in addition to
              routing intra-power domain and global nets using the  specifica-
              tions of the power domains.

              For  example,  when  you specify -handlePDComplex true, if a net
              belongs to power domains PD1 and PD3, but not PD2,  earlyGlobal-
              Route  routes  the  net  without going over the PD2 power domain
              boundary.

              Default: true

       -honorCpfGlobalConnectionSpecForAoBuffer {true | false}
              Honors connection pecs for AO buffer based on the CPF rules. Set
              true to enable.

              Default: false

       -honorCpfGlobalConnectionSpecForShifter {true | false}
              Honors connection specs for shifters based on the CPF rules. Set
              true to enable.

              Default: false

       -honorDotLibRelatedPGPin {true | false}
              Honors library related PG pins. Set true to enable.

              Default: true

       -honorEffectiveDomainForIsoLsInsertion {true | false}
              Honors effective domains for ISO/LS insertions. Set true to  en-
              able.

              Default: true

       -markIsoEnablePinAsAlwaysOn {true | false}
              Insert  ISO/LS for all the inter-domain nets using effective do-
              main based on the CPF rules. Set true to enable.

              Default: true

       -notUseTopFTermDomainForVoltage {true|false}
              Controls voltage using top fterm domain for IO pin voltage.

              Default: false

       -reset Resets the MSV mode to the default value. Any values that do not
              already match the default value and are reset. will be reported.

       -shareWellAOBufferingSupport {true|false}
              Shares the isolated Nwell AO buffers.

              Default: true

       -upf_allow_shifter_voltage_mismatch {true|false}
              When set to false, it prevents insertion of  level  shifters  by
              allowing voltage tolerance.

              Default: true

       -upf_insert_on_floating_pins {true|false}
              Allows  controlling  of low power cell insertion on the floating
              pins.

              Default: true

Examples
              * In the following example,allows the non-default  power  domain
                members  nested in the default power domain member are allowed
                logically and physically and this default power domain has the
                fence constraint:

                setMsvMode -allowNestedDefaultDomain true

              * In the following example, all the nets for the  iso/ls  inser-
                tion are checked:

                setMsvMode -checkAllNetsForDomainCrossing true

              * In  the  following  example, back-to-back isolation along with
                one net are inserted:

                setMsvMode -handleBackToBackIsolation true

              * In  the  following  example,  the  CPF   specification   (cre-
                ate_global_connection  -domain) are used for the ISO/LS PG pin
                connection:

                setMsvMode -honorCpfGlobalConnectionSpecForShifter true

              * In the following example, the pin  power  domain  is  assigned
                based on the related power pin specified in *.lib:

                setMsvMode -honorDotLibRelatedPGPin true

              * In  the following example, effective domain for the iso/ls in-
                sertion is used:

                setMsvMode -honorEffectiveDomainForIsoLsInsertion true

              * In the following example, the iso  enable  based  on  the  tag
                (power modes) is marked:

                setMsvMode -markIsoEnablePinAsAlwaysOn false

Related Information
